---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const nav = [
  { label: 'Overview', href: '#overview' },
  { label: 'Foundations', href: '#brand' },
  { label: 'Applications', href: '#applications' },
  { label: 'AI in Process', href: '#aiprocess' },
  { label: 'Reflection', href: '#reflection' },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="IXDA"
  heading="Building community through design"
  role="Creative Director, Designer"
  team="Solo Concept Project"
  timeline="1 week"
  projectType="Brand, Community"
  nav={nav}
>
  <section id="overview">
    <h3>context</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      My program did not have a year end show this year. So how might I use design to build a fresh
      and experience-lead event concept?
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="brand">
    <h3>inspiration</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I won the hoodie design challenge run annually by the IXDA club (Sheridan Interaction Design
      Association). Since this design is validated as popular choice by the students in my program,
      I thought to turn this one-off design into a brand system.
    </p>
    <h3>Concept</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Most people don't know what interaction design is. My hoodie design played on this, and drove
      the direction of my brand system. Create a space for audiences new to interaction design, a
      way to interact and experience it.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      My concept was to print the definition onto the sleeve. Budget constraints didn't allow, but
      the lesson stuck. Beyond strong visuals, audiences connect to interactive experiences.
    </p>
    <h3>brand tone</h3>
    <p class="lead">Minimal, bold, honest.</p>
    <h3>brand foundations</h3>
    <p>
      Typography is simple, letting the graphic elements and layout shine. Inter is also Figma's
      default font, calling back to the most used software in our program.
    </p>
    <p>
      Colour choice is simple and accessible in different combinations. Sheridan's brand colour is
      blue, but in a more vibrant tone.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Interaction Design Association runs the program's year end party and annual hoodie design
      challenge.
    </p>
    <p class="text-muted text-sm italic">*this logo was not designed by me</p>
    <p>
      This illustration represents our school mascot: the bruin, while also communicating a sense
      of reliability in it's tired stance.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="applications">
    <h3>applications</h3>
    <p>
      Every year, the IXDA club runs an award ceremony for new grads to vote on their peers during
      the year end party. My idea is that students can make their own award pins with their given
      superlative (or another tagline) as an activity to do with friends.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sticker sheet border is used as a photo frame for a photobooth! Website directory for this
      years new grad designers!
    </p>
    <p>
      Each attendee of the year end show gets a connect the dots card with a handwritten note and a
      way to keep track of which tables they have yet to visit! Each card has "interaction design"
      written in a different language.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every year, the IXDA club at Sheridan makes different limited edition pins that students can
      collect. This tote bag design helps students find a home for them!
    </p>
    <p>
      Instead of traditional large, crossbody portfolios, students can purchase our portfolio
      keychains to showcase their work in mini booklets and share their social links via NFC tags!
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="aiprocess">
    <h3>using ai in the process</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I used AI to generate mockups of my concepts. I used Figma Weave and AI tools within Figma and
      found that the tools/workflow doesn't matter as much as the context that you feed it.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      When I rely on flat lay designs that I designed only, it creates a design that is almost too
      perfect. When I use an award ribbon I made myself and took pictures of, it created a much more
      realistic mockup.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="reflection">
    <h3>Reflections</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Don't wait for permission</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Design and build what you want to see, even if it's not yet possible.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Explore different tools</h2>
        <p class="lead">Challenge myself to use new tools like Figma Weave.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="!mt-12">next steps</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Pitch to Faculty</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Now that the concept is built out, I want to bring this to reality by getting buy in from
          faculty and external sponsors.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Build a team</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Building out large scale events is not a task for one. Gathering a community of like minded
          students is important to making this concept feasible.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>
</CaseStudyLayout>
